In February 2026, Joe C. received renewed attention in the media after a controversial lyric from the [[Kid Rock]] song “Cool, Daddy Cool,” which features Joe C., resurfaced online. '''Taschen-Bibliothek der wichtigsten und interessantesten See- und Land-Reisen von der Erfindung der Buchdruckerkunst bis auf unsere Zeiten''' (''Pocket Library of the Most Important and Interesting Sea and Land Voyages from the Invention of the Art of Printing up to Our Times'') is a German book series compiled by multiple scholars. The editor was [[:de:Joachim Heinrich Jäck|Joachim Heinrich Jäck]] (1777–1847), a German Cistercian monk, librarian, local historian, and non-fiction author who served as Royal Librarian in [[Bamberg]]. It contains summaries of earlier travel accounts from the 16th to the early 19th centuries. The series comprised over 80 volumes and was published in Nuremberg by Haubenstricker and von Ebner between 1827 and 1836.<ref>[https://katalog.slub-dresden.de/id/0-130761044 Taschenbibliothek der wichtigsten und interessantesten See- und Landreisen]</ref> The series presents reports, maps, and illustrations in German of scientific, cultural, and geographic voyages and expeditions to regions such as India, Egypt, Greece, Persia, Palestine, the Ottoman Empire, China, Africa, and the world's oceans. It includes the journeys of notable explorers such as James Cook, George Dixon, Étienne Marchand, John Turnbull, and Adam Johann von Krusenstern.<ref>[https://www.zvab.com/Taschen-Bibliothek-wichtigsten-interessantesten-See--Land-Reisen-Erfindung/31405649936/bd photo] (ZVAB)</ref>

===Arrival in the Italian peninsula===

Spaghetti is made from grain ground into a flour and water.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Gisslen, Wayne |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzSwCGBHr3YC&pg=PA635 |title=Professional Cooking for Canadian Chefs |author2=Griffin, Mary Ellen |author3=Le Cordon Bleu |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |year=2006 |isbn=0-471-66377-8 |pages=635}}</ref> Whole-wheat and multigrain spaghetti are also sold.<ref name="nhg" /> Most spaghetti is produced in factories using auger [[Food extrusion|extruders]].
